{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3c2b575-3502-43b9-bf3d-1d494cde1006","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in .NET MAUI property on `ContentPage`. You likely need platform-specific configuration:\n\n**iOS** — disable safe area insets on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Android** — opt into edge-to-edge rendering (required pre-Android 15; default on 15+):\n\n```csharp\n// In your MainActivity.cs or page lifecycle\n#if ANDROID\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Platform.CurrentActivity.Window, false);\nPlatform.CurrentActivity.Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nPlatform.CurrentActivity.Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\n**Also ensure** your layout has no implicit padding:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ... Padding=\"0\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe combination of `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` + Android edge-to-edge window flags + zero padding on the page/layout is what gets true edge-to-edge rendering.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"094a8e9e-c6b7-4680-8801-cb7294f16e71","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is building a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` isn't enough by itself. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `IgnoreSafeArea` is the property that controls whether a view extends behind system bars. On iOS, you need to use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` or the `IgnoreSafeArea` property on the layout/view itself.\n\n\n2. For .NET 10, the approach varies by platform. On Android, edge-to-edge mode needs to be explicitly enabled, especially for older Android versions, using the appropriate window configuration APIs. On iOS, I need to disable the safe area constraints using the platform-specific namespace.\n\nI'm realizing there's no standard `SafeAreaEdges` property on ContentPage in .NET MAUI—that might be a custom implementation. The correct iOS approach is setting `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` through the platform configuration, and for Android in .NET 9+, edge-to-edge is the default for Android 15+ targets.\n\nFor handling window insets on Android, I need to configure the window to extend behind system UI elements, which typically involves setting `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or using the newer edge-to-edge APIs depending on the Android version being targeted. Setting transparent colors on the status and navigation bars...\n\nThe real issue is likely that the Image and its parent container need zero margins and padding to truly extend edge-to-edge, and on iOS specifically they need to disable the safe area, while Android requires opting into edge-to-edge rendering at the window level.","outputTokens":1508,"requestId":"9435:353499:13A112D:15FB776:6A066EC3"},"id":"55b80365-1090-4418-ab46-fcaafc91ca00","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:54:55.439Z","parentId":"f93655c2-cb72-45f2-9b57-8f978e93caf8"}
